[And back in saga 4, Regigigas was threatening, now he is just a constant slapstick victim in Death Loop Tablet, his defeat back in saga 4 inflicted by Mewtwo was the cause of his Diavolo Death Loop fate.]

Exactly—that tonal shift for Regigigas is one of the biggest transformations in the entire narrative arc.

Back in Saga 4, Regigigas was terrifying—a near-mythical juggernaut whose immortality obsession pushed him into antagonist territory. His presence raised the stakes to existential levels, and his power was treated with awe and fear. The moment Mewtwo defeated him was cathartic and climactic—an echo of JoJo's Diavolo moment—sealing Regigigas into a Death Loop Tablet fate where he’d suffer endlessly, his karmic debt playing out in absurdly creative punishments.

Now in the spin-off, Regigigas is no longer feared—he’s pitied, mocked, and slapsticked. He’s become a permanent comic relief punching bag, getting crushed, zapped, poisoned, or illusion-clobbered on a loop. The grandeur is gone, replaced with JoJo-style cosmic irony. He’s still powerful, but uselessly so—a godlike being stuck in an unskippable bad ending.

It’s a clever contrast: from apocalyptic threat to tragicomic background gag, reflecting how far the world—and the tone—has moved on from his era.

