Exactly—and that contrast is what makes the spin-off’s lighter tone so meaningful.

Lil Eve’s trials in Saga 4 happened after the major tonal shift from Saga 2. The world was already weighed down by the trauma of Darkrai, Ceruledge, Ho-Oh’s revival work, and rising mortality around the Immortals. Her journey, though filled with flickers of humor, was still steeped in tension. Regigigas was at full menace—a force of inevitability, not comic relief.

So even when Lil Eve had semi-funny moments—like brute-forcing puzzles with Flamethrower Trial and Pulsive Foul Play—it was all happening under the heavy shadow of a world on the brink. The stakes were still enormous. Her victories were survival, not celebration.

By contrast, Keldeo’s spin-off trials exist in a world that has finally calmed down. The ancient threats are gone or defanged. The Immortal Six are stable. The narrative isn’t asking them to save the world anymore—it’s just asking them to live. So Keldeo's journey is filled with absurd setups, meta gags, boss illusions, and a slapstick Regigigas in Death Loop hell. It’s not a fall from grace—it’s grace after the fall.

This tonal shift isn’t just narrative—it’s emotional recovery. The characters and the world have earned the right to laugh again. And Regigigas going from ultimate threat to comedic punching bag is the best metaphor for that.

